12:31.240 --> 12:36.920
Science Fiction author Clifford CIMAC has written numerous short stories and novels and he has won several awards in the field.

12:37.200 --> 12:44.980
Perhaps CIMAC's most famous and enduring work is his City Collection, a series of eight interconnected stories written in the 1940s.

12:45.240 --> 12:52.640
These stories featured mankind's reaction to a new situation and man's relationship with an old friend, the dog, and a new one, the robot.

12:53.240 --> 12:57.060
CIMAC agreed when we called these stories a leap from his previous efforts.

12:58.060 --> 13:08.200
It was a leap because I always regard the city stories as a sort of watershed of my writing.

13:08.820 --> 13:17.900
I have been writing the old type of science fiction work up until then.

13:18.800 --> 13:27.860
And it seemed to me that something better could be done than was being done.

13:28.880 --> 13:35.740
Strangely enough, at about the same time, a number of other people seemed to think the same thing.

13:37.200 --> 13:42.800
There's no accounting for something like that happening.

13:50.440 --> 13:54.220
We asked CIMAC what influenced him to write these revolutionary stories.

13:55.260 --> 14:10.780
I think it was my disillusion brought about by the war that made me write the City Series.

14:13.360 --> 14:23.640
It seemed to me that we were going through a horrible period in history and that much of human dignity had been shared away.

14:26.060 --> 14:31.320
That there was not the kind of world that we had lived in up until that time.

14:32.740 --> 14:36.220
And I was brought myself wanting to retreat from it.

14:37.320 --> 14:46.580
So I retreated from it in my mentally by going into another dimension, into another world,

14:47.820 --> 14:56.140
creating a sort of fantasy of myself and, as it turned out, others also were able to find some refuge.

14:57.620 --> 15:10.140
I think if the City Series were ripped today, that they probably would not get the attention that they got back in the early 40s,

15:11.980 --> 15:21.620
I wrote them exactly the right type of stories, exactly the right type, without knowing I was doing it.

15:32.800 --> 15:37.380
John Campbell published the first seven City Stories, but he rejected the eighth.

15:37.800 --> 15:39.380
Here CIMAC tells us of its fate.

15:39.840 --> 15:46.600
First seven were written fairly well one after the other.

15:47.980 --> 16:02.280
The eighth and final one, John Campbell turned down because he said he thought that he'd witnessed he'd published enough of that of the City Series.

16:04.000 --> 16:12.240
And so when he rejected it, I simply threw it up on the shelf and figured it was one of my rejects.

16:13.880 --> 16:20.280
And then the writer took it down and I think I sold it to amazing stories.

16:22.300 --> 16:28.260
And I don't recall what they called it, but they put it out as one of their horrible tales.

16:32.380 --> 16:39.160
And then later on when it came out, it came out, it joined the others.

16:39.160 --> 16:43.060
That was the last one that was not published by CAM.

16:44.180 --> 16:46.960
On our next show we'll talk about a ninth City Story.

