18:23.480 --> 18:27.880
Science fiction writer Clifford Simac's most famous work is his story collection, City.

18:28.620 --> 18:33.360
This collection of eight connected short stories was first published as a body by Nome in 1952.

18:33.620 --> 18:37.620
Here's afterwards Simac was persuaded to write a ninth City Story, Epilogue.

18:38.160 --> 18:39.680
Here he explains its genesis.

18:41.180 --> 18:43.020
Well John Camel died.

18:44.380 --> 18:51.820
And of course all of us, all of us were stricken by his death because he was a comparatively young man

18:51.820 --> 18:55.460
and appeared to be in good physical condition.

18:57.960 --> 19:06.140
Some of the writers reverenced him, I'm not too sure I reverenced him, but I felt very kindly to him,

19:06.140 --> 19:08.540
he was very badly hit by his death.

19:10.440 --> 19:18.000
And a group of the writers got together and said we'd have to put out a memorial to John Camel.

19:18.980 --> 19:28.680
And the best way to do it would be to put out the last issue of the oldest downing stories,

19:28.820 --> 19:31.180
not analog, but the oldest downing stories.

19:32.960 --> 19:43.500
And so they asked, I suppose there were a dozen or so people who had written for the oldest downing stories

19:43.500 --> 19:47.160
to write a story for the Memorial Lulley.

19:48.160 --> 19:57.020
And Harry Harris who was the editor told me and he said Cliff if you will write a story,

19:57.240 --> 19:59.020
I wish you'd write another City Story.

20:02.300 --> 20:13.200
And I was reluctant to do that, I should have awakened it because it had been quite a number of years since I'd written a City Story.

20:14.680 --> 20:22.360
And I knew that I had said I was a changed writer, I was not the same man as I was when I'd written the stories.

20:24.880 --> 20:34.060
I worried a great deal about the propriety of writing another City Story because I figured that the last one, the last of eight,

20:34.740 --> 20:41.760
had wound up the story of the Webster family and that there was no need to go in further.

20:43.460 --> 20:50.880
But the more I thought about it, the more I began to see that if I was going to write something for that Memorial about volume,

20:50.880 --> 20:53.120
it should be a City Story.

20:55.060 --> 21:09.180
So for the first time since I'd written them, I took down my copy of the book City and reread it, trying to catch the flavor and the spirit of the stories.

21:10.340 --> 21:21.520
And when I read the stories, I simply absolutely ached to rewrite them again because there are some awful clouties in them.

21:22.460 --> 21:31.200
But I knew even as I thought about that, that I couldn't do it because if I rewrote them, they wouldn't be a City Story.

21:32.820 --> 21:44.520
So I sat down and did my best to try to recreate the flavor of the other eight stories.

21:45.740 --> 21:51.220
I think I came very close to it, but not as satisfactorily as I'd have wanted to.

21:52.340 --> 21:56.320
Ace published the nine stories as a group for the first time in 1981.

21:56.320 --> 22:02.280
The robots in City are gentle, respectful entities. We asked Simac why he made them so.

22:03.480 --> 22:10.180
Most of the writers who had written robots before wrote of them as machines.

22:12.000 --> 22:17.620
And I wrote of them as surrogate human beings.

22:19.760 --> 22:30.760
I made them people with some of the biases and prejudices that the living human would have stripped away from them.

22:31.940 --> 22:37.080
And I tried to make them the kind of people that I would want to live with.

22:37.640 --> 22:39.800
More on Clifford Simac on our next show.

